                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14459644" author="jstrachan" created="Tue, 25 Nov 2003 12:53:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I thought I&apos;d assign this one to you as you mentioned you wanted regexp support &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14459692" author="jstrachan" created="Wed, 26 Nov 2003 02:25:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;FYI...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ruby-lang.org/en/man-1.4/syntax.html#regexp&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://www.ruby-lang.org/en/man-1.4/syntax.html#regexp&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14459737" author="spullara" created="Fri, 28 Nov 2003 16:57:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Bob and I were discussing the lexer/parser problems that /.../ introduces or even %r?...? introduces and thought maybe it could be made simpler by putting the weight of the problem on an operator instead that would convert strings to regular expressions.  For instance:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;text ~= &quot;blah&quot;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;returns list of matching components&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This would allow us to automatically use the ${foo} syntax in the regex and things like that.  It would also make it really easy to use any string as a regex.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14459578" author="spullara" created="Fri, 28 Nov 2003 22:43:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve got an implementation that works like this right now:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;string ~= regex&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;will return a Matcher.  When you evaluate it as a boolean it calls .find() on it so you can loop over the result if you like:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;m = &quot;blahblah&quot; ~= &quot;blah&quot;&lt;br/&gt;
while (m) {&lt;br/&gt;
  println(m.group()) &lt;br/&gt;
}&lt;br/&gt;
(prints &apos;blah&apos; twice)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;and you can also get the information about the match from the matcher.  If you use this form:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;blah&quot; ~== &quot;blah&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It does an exact match only.  The entire string must match pattern.  What do people think about this implementation?  It certainly isn&apos;t the same as Ruby&apos;s but I think that it is more in the spirit of using the available Java class libraries.  I also like how it is similar to the other comparison functions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sidenote: is there some reason i don&apos;t understand for putting &apos;s on either side of a string printed by itself?  its weird and very surprising.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14459758" author="spullara" created="Fri, 28 Nov 2003 22:49:40 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure what the best way to surface this is in a switch statement.  I&apos;ll have to think about that one and discuss.  I suppose it could be as easy as:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;expr = &quot;blah&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;switch ( expr ) {&lt;br/&gt;
    case expr ~= regex:&lt;br/&gt;
      ...&lt;br/&gt;
}&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Not sure how that syntax sits with everyone.  Should be fine if we are going to have arbitrary expressions for case statements.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14459645" author="spullara" created="Sat, 29 Nov 2003 00:16:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m going to go ahead and check-in so people have something to play with.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14459693" author="spullara" created="Mon, 1 Dec 2003 14:40:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Added ~&amp;lt;double quoted string&amp;gt; syntax for creating precompiled patterns.  All use cases are now complete.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
